docs.abstract: Wall Street, roiled this week by the most turbulence in years, broke from a brief respite on Thursday, entering a market correction.
docs.snippet: Wall Street, roiled this week by the most turbulence in years, broke from a brief respite on Thursday, entering a market correction.
docs.lead_paragraph: After watching stocks march higher for nearly nine years, investors are suddenly confronting a new reality: The long, smooth ride is over. And it doesn’t feel good.

headline.main: Stocks Plunge as Market Enters ‘Correction’ Territory
headline.print_headline: Another Dive Puts Market in Correction Territory

byline.original: By Matt Phillips and Tiffany Hsu

docs.abstract: A report outlining years of sexual misconduct by Mr. Wynn sent shares in his company, Wynn Resorts, plummeting and raised questions about his future in Republican politics.
docs.snippet: A report outlining years of sexual misconduct by Mr. Wynn sent shares in his company, Wynn Resorts, plummeting and raised questions about his future in Republican politics.
docs.lead_paragraph: Stephen Wynn’s perch at the top of the casino industry was badly shaken on Friday following the disclosure of allegations that he engaged in a long pattern of sexual misconduct with employees of his casinos.

headline.main: Stephen Wynn, Casino Mogul, Accused of Decades of Sexual Misconduct
headline.print_headline: Casino Mogul  Is Accused  Of Misconduct  Over Decades

byline.original: By Matthew Goldstein, Tiffany Hsu and Kenneth P. Vogel

docs.abstract: Our reporter helps you make sense of what is happening in stock, bonds and your portfolio.
docs.snippet: Our reporter helps you make sense of what is happening in stock, bonds and your portfolio.
docs.lead_paragraph: The stock markets have taken investors for a wild ride over the past week, with jitters in the United States spreading around the world. When the markets behave erratically, anxieties escalate and questions naturally arise.

headline.main: The Times Answers Your Questions About the Market Turmoil

docs.abstract: Final arguments in the Justice Department’s lawsuit seeking the block the merger were made on Monday, and Judge Richard J. Leon is expected to rule on June 12. He has given few signs of his thinking.
docs.snippet: Final arguments in the Justice Department’s lawsuit seeking the block the merger were made on Monday, and Judge Richard J. Leon is expected to rule on June 12. He has given few signs of his thinking.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Lawyers faced off over the future of AT&T’s $85.4 billion blockbuster merger with Time Warner for a final time in a courtroom on Monday, sparring over what the deal would mean to consumers.

headline.main: Would AT&T’s Time Warner Deal Help or Hurt Consumers? Judge Will Now Decide
headline.print_headline: Future of Deal Between Time Warner And AT&T Is Now in a Judge’s Hands

docs.abstract: The decision by a federal judge hampers the company’s argument that politics influenced the government’s move to block its $85 billion merger with Time Warner.
docs.snippet: The decision by a federal judge hampers the company’s argument that politics influenced the government’s move to block its $85 billion merger with Time Warner.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — A federal judge blocked AT&T’s move to obtain communication logs between the Justice Department and the White House on Tuesday, hampering the phone giant’s argument that politics played a role in the government’s decision to halt a merger with Time Warner.

headline.main: AT&T Loses Bid to Obtain White House Call Logs
headline.print_headline: AT&T Loses Bid to See White House Call Logs In Battle Over Merger

docs.abstract: The announcement, by the Internet Association, made clear that companies like Google, Facebook and Netflix would back a legal fight.
docs.snippet: The announcement, by the Internet Association, made clear that companies like Google, Facebook and Netflix would back a legal fight.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — An industry group that represents the country’s biggest technology companies said on Friday that it planned to join a looming legal fight against the Federal Communications Commission over its repeal of so-called net neutrality rules.

headline.main: Big Tech to Join Legal Fight Against Net Neutrality Repeal
headline.print_headline: Big Tech to Fight Net Neutrality Repeal

docs.abstract: The law is the most sweeping state action so far against new federal rules that strip away regulations on how high-speed internet providers handle digital data.
docs.snippet: The law is the most sweeping state action so far against new federal rules that strip away regulations on how high-speed internet providers handle digital data.
docs.lead_paragraph: Residents of Washington State are getting so-called net neutrality rules back, with the nation’s first state law that prevents internet service providers from blocking and slowing down content online.

headline.main: Washington Governor Signs First State Net Neutrality Bill
headline.print_headline: Net Neutrality Revived in Washington State

docs.abstract: In a letter organized by the Campaign for a Commercial-Free Childhood, dozens of health experts say the new app preys on a vulnerable group.
docs.snippet: In a letter organized by the Campaign for a Commercial-Free Childhood, dozens of health experts say the new app preys on a vulnerable group.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — At the age of 6, a child is full of imagination and may not distinguish reality from fantasy. She is beginning to read and can’t grasp nuances in written communication. She also doesn’t understand privacy.

headline.main: Turn Off Messenger Kids, Health Experts Plead to Facebook
headline.print_headline: Turn Off Messenger Kids, Health Experts Plead in a Letter to Facebook

docs.abstract: President Trump’s sudden decision to halt Broadcom’s bid to take over Qualcomm reflects a concerted effort to protect American companies from China.
docs.snippet: President Trump’s sudden decision to halt Broadcom’s bid to take over Qualcomm reflects a concerted effort to protect American companies from China.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump’s swift decision this week to block a Singapore-based company from gaining control of Qualcomm grew out of a White House push to wall off American industry from foreign competition, primarily China, under the guise of protecting national security.

headline.main: Trump’s Killing of Chip Deal Pushes Protectionism as It Invokes Security
headline.print_headline: Administration Practices Protectionism by Invoking National Security

byline.original: By Ana Swanson, Cecilia Kang and Alan Rappeport

docs.abstract: The company was accused of collecting data on children without parents’ permission and failing to keep it secure from hackers. It agreed to pay $650,000.
docs.snippet: The company was accused of collecting data on children without parents’ permission and failing to keep it secure from hackers. It agreed to pay $650,000.
docs.lead_paragraph: The popular electronic toymaker VTech Electronics agreed to pay $650,000 to settle charges that it had collected digital data on children without parents’ permission and failed to keep that information secure from hackers, the Federal Trade Commission said Monday.

headline.main: Toymaker VTech Settles Charges of Violating Child Privacy Law
headline.print_headline: Toymaker VTech Settles  In Child Privacy Law Case
